mmon than they knew. Chronicling a critical episode in the development of modem scholarship, The Battle of the Books illuminates the roots of present-day controversies about the role of the classics in the curriculum and the place of the humanities in education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAncients and moderns, Quarrel of. 0aClassical literaturexAppreciationzGreat Britain. 0aClassical literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aClassicismzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aClassicismzGreat Britain. 0aComparative literaturexClassical and modern. 0aComparative literaturexModern and classical. 0aCriticismzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHistoriographyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 4aEngland. 4aHistory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172764140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501727641423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501727641/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles